{"result":{"tools":[{"name":"remember","description":"Append a single fact line to the user's long-term memory. Writes to the master log facts-<userId>.md AND mirrors to a per-topic shard facts_Topic/<userId>/<topic>.md. Pass `topic` to force the shard (must match a name in topics.json); omit it to let the server classify via the same rules used for the preamble topic index. Use this to store stable user preferences, decisions, or project facts that should survive across chat sessions. One fact per call; short, self-contained sentences work best.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"text":{"type":"string","description":"The fact to remember (a single short sentence)."},"topic":{"type":"string","description":"Optional: explicit topic name (see preamble 'Memory topics'). When omitted, the server auto-classifies using topics.json."}},"required":["text"]}},{"name":"list_facts","description":"Return stored long-term memory facts for this user (timestamps stripped). Preferred usage: pass `query` = a topic name from the preamble topic index (e.g. 'bridge-token', 'scheduler') — the server reads that shard file directly AND returns the entire shard regardless of `tail` (shards are already small classified sets). If you want to narrow a shard read, pass an explicit `tail` in the call. For any other `query` string the server falls back to a case-insensitive substring scan over the master log, where `tail` (default 20) caps the result. Pass `tail=0` to disable the cap on a master scan.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"tail":{"type":"number","description":"Cap on results. For master-log substring scans, default 20 (pass 0 to return all matches). For topic-shard reads (when query matches a topic name), the cap is ignored unless you pass an explicit number — the full shard is returned by default."},"query":{"type":"string","description":"Topic name from the preamble index (expands to keyword OR-match) or any case-insensitive substring."}}}},{"name":"forget","description":"Delete facts from the user's long-term memory by case-insensitive substring match on the master log. Two-phase flow: 1) call with `query` only — if 0 matches returns an error, if exactly 1 match it is deleted immediately, if ≥2 matches it returns the candidates plus a `confirm` token and deletes nothing; 2) call again with the same `query` plus `confirm` set to that token to actually delete all matches. Any change to the master log between preview and confirm invalidates the token (you'll need to re-preview). Every delete is mirrored to all topic shards (via rebuild) and logged to forget-log.md for audit. Use this to clean up test/smoke facts or to remove stale notes — never delete silently without showing the user what's going.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"query":{"type":"string","description":"Case-insensitive substring matched against each fact's text (timestamp/bullet stripped). Short distinctive phrases work best — e.g. 'facts-smoke-test' rather than a single common word."},"confirm":{"type":"string","description":"Confirmation token returned by the first call when multiple matches are found. Pass it back unchanged to commit the delete. Omit on the first call."}},"required":["query"]}},{"name":"propose_topics","description":"Read-only snapshot for a /topic-review pass. Returns the full list of facts (oldest first), the currently-active topics.json, per-topic shard counts, and the max-topics limit. No writes, no side effects. Use this to decide whether the current topic set still fits the master log. After you decide on a new list, call `apply_topics` with the proposed `topics` array to commit. Never call `apply_topics` without first calling `propose_topics` in the same turn — you need the fresh snapshot to make a sensible proposal.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{}}},{"name":"apply_topics","description":"Overwrite topics.json with a new topic list and rebuild all shards from the master log. Input `topics` must be a non-empty array of { topic: string, keywords: string[] } with unique lowercase topic names (a-z, 0-9, _, -) and ≤50 entries by default (configurable via MEMORY_MAX_TOPICS). The server validates, snapshots the old file to topics.bak.<ts>.json, writes the new file, invalidates the in-process cache, and rebuilds every topic shard so existing facts are re-classified immediately. Returns the new shard histogram so you can show the user what moved. Optionally pass `expectedToken` (from a previous call) to guard against racing edits — the server recomputes the token from the normalised proposal and rejects the call on mismatch.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"topics":{"type":"array","description":"Proposed topic list. Each entry: { topic: string (slug, ≤40 chars), keywords: string[] (≥1 non-empty substring) }. Order matters — first-match-wins during classification, so put more-specific topics before broader ones.","items":{"type":"object","properties":{"topic":{"type":"string"},"keywords":{"type":"array","items":{"type":"string"}}},"required":["topic","keywords"]}},"expectedToken":{"type":"string","description":"Optional. If provided, must equal computeTopicsToken(normalised proposal). Use the token printed by a previous apply_topics or a user-approved dry-run to prevent double-apply."}},"required":["topics"]}},{"name":"ingest_prepare","description":"Fetch a URL or local file, split into chunks, save raw chunks. Returns chunk summaries for you to build a hierarchical tree index. After reviewing summaries, call ingest_save with your tree JSON.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"source":{"type":"string","description":"URL (http/https) or absolute file path to ingest."},"slug":{"type":"string","description":"Short identifier for this index (a-z, 0-9, hyphens). Auto-generated from source if omitted."}},"required":["source"]}},{"name":"ingest_save","description":"Save the tree index JSON you built from ingest_prepare summaries. The tree should have { summary, children: [...] } with chunk_ids at leaf nodes referencing chunk indices from ingest_prepare.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"slug":{"type":"string","description":"Must match the slug returned by ingest_prepare."},"title":{"type":"string","description":"Human-readable title for this document index."},"tree":{"type":"object","description":"Hierarchical tree: { summary: string, children: [{ summary, children|chunk_ids }] }. Leaf nodes must have chunk_ids: number[] pointing to chunk indices."}},"required":["slug","tree"]}},{"name":"list_indexes","description":"List all document tree indexes available in the indexes directory. Use this to see what documents have been ingested for tree-based retrieval.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{}}},{"name":"query_index","description":"Query a document tree index by question. Navigates the tree using embedding similarity (or keyword fallback) and returns the most relevant chunks. Much faster than manually reading the index JSON.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"slug":{"type":"string","description":"Index slug to query (from list_indexes)."},"question":{"type":"string","description":"The question to find relevant chunks for."},"max_chunks":{"type":"number","description":"Max chunks to return (default 3)."}},"required":["slug","question"]}},{"name":"ingest_update","description":"Incrementally update an existing index by re-reading its source. Diffs chunks, remaps the tree, and appends new/changed sections as an '_updated' branch. Agent should then restructure the tree if needed via ingest_save.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"slug":{"type":"string","description":"Slug of the existing index to update."}},"required":["slug"]}},{"name":"build_cross_refs","description":"Build cross-references between document indexes. Finds semantically related chunks across different indexes and stores links in each index's tree nodes. Requires embedding router to be active.","inputSchema":{"type":"object","properties":{"slugs":{"type":"array","items":{"type":"string"},"description":"Slugs to process (omit for all indexes)."},"threshold":{"type":"number","description":"Cosine similarity threshold for cross-ref (default 0.7)."}}}}]},"jsonrpc":"2.0","id":2}
